    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "### Problem\n\nAs far as I can tell, there is currently no way to generate documentation for `--- @alias`. This can be useful to not duplicate documentation and be able to use aliases.\n\nFor example, this came up in #39570. There is a field `scope` that can take a non-trivial amount of values which might later be reused in different functions. Creating `--- @alias vim.Scope 'cursor'|...` did not generate a documentation for it while used `` {scope}? (`vim.Scope`) `` in generated documentation (i.e. allowed values are not documented anywhere).\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nBe able to extract a common used field in a `--- @alias` and it will be documented somewhere with its own tag. So that it can be reused in other documentation when this alias is used in annotations.",
    "closed_at": null,
    "closed_by": null,
    "comment_data": [
        {
            "author_association": "NONE",
            "body": "I'd like to work on this as my first OSS contribution. I'm new to Neovim's codebase but I've been using Neovim daily for a while.\n \nBefore I start, I'd like to clarify the expected output format:\n- Should aliases be documented as separate sections (e.g., `*vim.Scope*`) with their union values listed?\n- Where should these sections appear in the generated `.txt` files? A dedicated \"Types\" section, or inline with the module?\n \nThanks for any guidance!",
            "created_at": "2026-05-18T14:03:28Z",
